    <article class="content-article">
      <p>I've replaced hundreds of LG dryer igniters over the years, and I can tell you that nine times out of ten, when your gas dryer isn't heating, it's that little ceramic igniter that's cracked. Most homeowners don't realize these parts only last about 3-5 years before the constant heating and cooling causes them to fail.</p>
<h2>Signs Your LG Dryer Igniter Needs Replacement</h2>
<p>The first thing we check when a customer calls about their LG dryer not heating is the igniter. You'll hear the dryer running, the drum turning, but clothes come out damp after a full cycle. Here's what's happening: the igniter glows orange for about 90 seconds trying to light the gas, but if it's weak or cracked, it can't draw enough current to open the gas valve solenoid.

I've seen igniters that look perfectly fine to the naked eye but are actually cracked internally. Sometimes you can spot a visible crack in the ceramic, but more often the failure is electrical. The igniter will glow, but not bright enough to signal the control board to release gas. Our techs use a multimeter to test the current draw - a good igniter pulls about 3.2 to 3.6 amps when it's working properly.</p>
<h3>Testing Your Igniter's Performance</h3>
<p>Don't try to test the igniter yourself by looking at the glow - that's not reliable. We measure the actual amperage draw because an igniter can appear to work but still be too weak to trigger the gas valve. If you're comfortable with electrical testing, you can check continuity, but for safety reasons, I recommend calling us for proper diagnosis.</p>
<h2>The Igniter Replacement Process: What We Do</h2>
<p>Replacing an LG dryer igniter isn't complicated, but it requires the right approach. We start by disconnecting the gas line and electrical connections - never skip this step. The igniter sits right next to the burner assembly, held in place by two mounting screws. The ceramic is extremely fragile, so we handle it like we're working with an eggshell.

Our techs only use OEM LG igniters, never aftermarket parts. I've seen too many callbacks from generic igniters that fail within months. The OEM part costs a bit more upfront, but it's designed specifically for your dryer's gas valve timing and electrical requirements. We also inspect the gas valve solenoid coils while we're in there - about 20% of the time, we find they need replacement too.</p>
<h3>Why Professional Installation Matters</h3>
<p>One wrong connection on the gas side and you've got a serious safety hazard. We check the gas pressure, test all connections with leak detection solution, and verify the flame sensor is working properly. The whole job takes about 45 minutes when done right, including proper testing of the heating cycle.</p>
<h2>Cost Breakdown: DIY vs Professional Repair</h2>
<p>The OEM LG igniter part costs around $45-65 depending on your model. Add basic tools if you don't have them, and you're looking at maybe $80 total for a DIY repair. Sounds reasonable, right? Here's what I've learned from years in the field: about 30% of DIY igniter replacements I see later have problems - usually gas leaks or improper connections.

Our service call runs $65 for diagnosis (waived if you repair with us), plus parts and labor. Total job usually comes to $160-180. That includes proper testing, warranty on the part, and peace of mind that your gas connections are safe. I've seen homeowners in Burbank who tried to save money end up calling us anyway when their 'fixed' dryer still wouldn't heat properly.</p>
<h3>Hidden Costs of DIY Repairs</h3>
<p>Beyond the safety concerns, DIY repairs often miss related problems. We typically find issues with the thermal fuse, lint buildup affecting airflow, or gas valve problems that a homeowner wouldn't catch. Fixing just the igniter without addressing these issues leads to premature failure of the new part.</p>
<h2>Common LG Dryer Models and Igniter Differences</h2>
<p>Not all LG igniters are created equal. The newer ThinQ models use a slightly different igniter design than the older DLGX series. I've worked on everything from the basic DLE models to the high-end Signature series, and each has specific requirements for igniter placement and electrical connections.

The DLEX models, which are pretty common in Orange County homes, have an igniter that's easier to access than some other brands. Still, the gas valve solenoid setup is sensitive - you need to make sure the new igniter draws the right amperage to properly signal the control board. We keep igniters for all major LG series on our trucks, so we can usually complete the repair in one visit.</p>
<h3>Model-Specific Installation Notes</h3>
<p>DLGX models from 2018 and newer have a bracket design that's slightly different from earlier versions. The mounting screws are in the same position, but the electrical connector has changed. We always verify the exact part number before starting any repair to avoid compatibility issues.</p>
<h2>Preventing Future Igniter Failures</h2>
<p>Most LG dryer igniters fail from normal wear and tear, but you can extend their life with proper maintenance. The biggest killer is restricted airflow - when your dryer can't exhaust properly, it runs longer cycles and puts extra stress on the igniter. Clean your lint filter after every load, and have the exhaust vent cleaned annually.

I've noticed that homes with hard water tend to have more igniter problems. The minerals seem to affect the electrical components over time. If you're in an area with hard water, consider having your dryer serviced every 18 months instead of waiting for problems. Our 85% first-visit fix rate comes from catching these issues early during routine maintenance calls.</p>
<h3>Signs to Call for Service</h3>
<p>Don't wait for complete failure. If your drying times are getting longer, or you notice the dryer running multiple cycles to get clothes dry, have us check the igniter. Early replacement prevents damage to other components and keeps your energy costs down.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>How do I know if my LG dryer igniter is bad?</h3>
<p>The most obvious sign is your dryer running but not heating - clothes come out damp after a full cycle. You might hear the dryer start, run for a few minutes, then stop and restart. If you look inside the front panel, you might see the igniter glowing orange but the gas never lights. Don't rely on just visual inspection though - we use electrical testing to determine if the igniter is drawing enough current to properly open the gas valve.</p>
<h3>What tools do I need to replace an LG dryer igniter?</h3>
<p>Basic hand tools - screwdrivers, socket set, and needle-nose pliers. More importantly, you need a multimeter to test the electrical connections and leak detection solution for the gas fittings. The real challenge isn't the tools, it's knowing how to safely disconnect the gas line and properly test the repair. I've seen too many DIY jobs where the gas connections weren't properly sealed.</p>
<h3>How much does it cost to replace an LG dryer igniter?</h3>
<p>The OEM part runs about $45-65 depending on your model. Our complete service including diagnosis, part, and labor typically costs $160-180. That includes testing all the related components and making sure everything is working safely. We waive the $65 diagnostic fee if you have us do the repair, so you're really looking at about $115 in labor and markup on the part.</p>
<h3>Can I replace my LG dryer igniter myself?</h3>
<p>Technically yes, but I don't recommend it unless you're very comfortable working with gas appliances. The igniter replacement itself is straightforward, but you're working around gas lines and electrical connections. One mistake can create a dangerous situation. About 30% of the DIY igniter jobs I see later have safety issues or don't work properly because related problems weren't addressed.</p>
<h3>How long should an LG dryer igniter last?</h3>
<p>Typically 3-5 years with normal use. I've seen them last up to 8 years in homes where the dryer is used lightly and well-maintained, but they can fail in as little as 2 years if you have restricted airflow or run a lot of heavy loads. The constant heating and cooling causes the ceramic to crack eventually - it's just normal wear. Keeping your lint filter clean and having regular maintenance helps extend the life.</p>
    <h2>Schedule Same-Day LG Dryer Repair</h2>
    <p>If your LG dryer isn't heating properly, don't spend your weekend wrestling with gas lines and electrical connections. Call us at (323) 990-7550 and we'll have a tech out the same day, Monday through Saturday. We'll diagnose the problem for $65 (waived if you repair with us), and if it's the igniter, we'll have you back to properly dried clothes within the hour. We stock OEM parts for all LG models and back our work with a solid warranty.</p>
